GLOBAL
Maritime law: contracts bind under the law of last port of registry; no
magistrate at sea, so agreements are self-enforcing or disputed at destination
Cargo manifests must match what is actually loaded; discrepancies become legal
liability at the destination port
Harbor fees and berthing schedules vary by port; experienced captains read
local weather signals, not just the sky
Tides: coastal cities time gate and dock operations to tidal cycles; inland
traders often underestimate this constraint
~
KOWLOON
Delta runs four gates: Jade (north, diplomatic), Iron (caravan frontier,
heaviest traffic), Lantern (west, oil lamps left by travelers who made it
home), Tide (harbor-facing, widest, for cargo wagons and grain barges)
Harbor Syndics in blue sashes audit every cargo manifest; their operations
are intertwined with smuggling networks — enforcement is selective by design
River Corsairs under Captain Blacktide Shen probe gate timings regularly;
their movement reports worth coin at the Warden of Iron's office
Coppersalt Bay weather changes fast; experienced pilots read mountain thermals,
not the sky; sudden storm squalls are common in monsoon season
Signal-lantern relay network extends toward Midgaard road corridor; maritime
alerts can reach Midgaard in hours via the Courier Lantern Office relay
~
KIESS
Primarily a road city; limited harbor operations; maritime trade arrives via
Kowloon and Mafdet after overland transfer at Midgaard
River access exists but is minor compared to Roc Road overland traffic
Wall Command monitors any vessels using coastal approaches; they are not
harbor specialists and process maritime arrivals slowly
~
MAFDET
Harbor chain raises every night without exception — never failed since the
Fracture Era; arriving ships after dark anchor outside and wait for dawn
Harbor Wardens control quay security; Warden-Commander's Harbor Register
holds 100+ years of vessel/cargo/crew/weather records
Dual attestation required: both inland and maritime legal standards on all
cargo; Shoreward House provides bilingual clerks for this
Trade oaths at the First Claw are binding and permanent; Swift Court decides
disputes within three tides; no appeal except to full Shrine council
Quarantine Ledger handles relic and hazardous goods from pyramid corridor;
most sensitive Ledger House; recent seizures under sealed review
~
